CYBV311 Introduction to Security Programming II - Assembly Language
===================================================================

This git repository is a learning resource for the CYBV311 Introduction to
Security Programming II course. It contains a small "Hello World" program
written in x86 assembly (see HelloWorldASM/hello.asm) that you build and run
from Visual Studio.

The assembly files in this project are written for the NASM assembler and are
built as 32-bit (x86 / Win32) programs. NASM assembles the .asm file into an
object file, and the Visual Studio (MSVC) linker links it into an executable.


Requirements
------------

  * Visual Studio 2026 (the Community edition is free) with the
    "Desktop development with C++" workload installed.
  * The NASM assembler for Windows.
  * VSNASM, which teaches Visual Studio how to build .asm files with NASM.


Step 1 - Install NASM
---------------------

Download the latest Windows build of NASM here:

  https://www.nasm.us/pub/nasm/releasebuilds/?C=M;O=D

Run the installer (or unzip the archive) and install to the default location:

  C:\Program Files\NASM

Confirm that nasm.exe exists in that folder before continuing.


Step 2 - Install VSNASM (NASM build integration for Visual Studio)
------------------------------------------------------------------

Visual Studio does not know how to build .asm files on its own. VSNASM adds
the "NASM" build customization (nasm.props / nasm.targets) that this project's
.vcxproj already references.

  https://github.com/ShiftMediaProject/VSNASM

Follow the instructions in the VSNASM README. The install.bat script is the
easiest path - it copies the build customization files into your Visual Studio
installation automatically. Manual installation instructions are also provided
if you prefer to copy the files yourself.


Step 3 - Point Visual Studio at nasm.exe
----------------------------------------

Add the NASM install folder to the "Build Customization Search Path" so Visual
Studio can find nasm.exe when it runs the custom build step. In Visual Studio
2026, this setting is under:

  Tools -> Options -> Projects and Solutions -> VC++ Project Settings

Add the NASM install folder to the search path, for example:

  C:\Program Files\NASM

(This is the default NASM installation location on Windows.)


Step 4 - Open, build, and run
-----------------------------

  1. Open CYBV311.sln in Visual Studio 2026.
  2. If Visual Studio prompts to retarget the project, accept it - this project
     is configured for the v145 platform toolset that ships with VS 2026.
  3. Set the Solution Platform to x86 (Win32). This program uses 32-bit name
     decoration (e.g. _main, _ExitProcess@4), so it must be built for x86.
  4. Build the solution (Build -> Build Solution, or Ctrl+Shift+B).
  5. Run it (Debug -> Start Without Debugging, or Ctrl+F5) to see the greeting.


Notes for older Visual Studio versions
---------------------------------------

These project files were originally created with Visual Studio 2019 (platform
toolset v142) and have been updated for Visual Studio 2026 (platform toolset
v145). If you open the solution in Visual Studio 2022, accept the retarget
prompt and it will build with the v143 toolset.
